In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims May 12-18, 2013, as National Women's Health Week in the United States. He highlights the progress that has been made in women's health and well-being, but acknowledges that there is still work to be done. Obama mentions the Affordable Care Act, which has provided women with more control over their health and eliminated discriminatory practices by insurance companies. He emphasizes the importance of preventive services and improved prescription drug coverage, which have benefited millions of women across the country. Obama encourages women to access resources available to them, such as www.WomensHealth.gov, www.GirlsHealth.gov, and www.HealthCare.gov. He concludes by urging Americans to celebrate the progress made in protecting women's health and to promote activities that improve the health of all women.